@joel-costigliola I'm still seeing this problem in the latest version(3.25.3)

Code:
```
import static org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat;

import java.util.List;
import org.assertj.core.api.Assertions;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;

public class AssertJNestedTest {

  @Test
  public void test() {
    Assertions.setRemoveAssertJRelatedElementsFromStackTrace(false);

    List<Integer> list = List.of(1, 2, 3, 4);
    assertThat(list)
        .satisfiesOnlyOnce(
            n -> {
              isFive(n);
            });
  }

  private static void isFive(int n) {
    assertThat(n).isEqualTo(5);
  }
}
```

Exception
```
AssertJNestedTest > test() FAILED
    java.lang.AssertionError:
    Expecting exactly one element of actual:
      [1, 2, 3, 4]
    to satisfy the requirements but none did
        at org.assertj.core.error.AssertionErrorCreator.assertionError(AssertionErrorCreator.java:93)
        at org.assertj.core.internal.Failures.failure(Failures.java:126)
        at org.assertj.core.internal.Iterables.assertSatisfiesOnlyOnce(Iterables.java:1241)
        at org.assertj.core.api.AbstractIterableAssert.satisfiesOnlyOnceForProxy(AbstractIterableAssert.java:3998)
        at org.assertj.core.api.AbstractIterableAssert.satisfiesOnlyOnce(AbstractIterableAssert.java:3991)
        at software.amazon.opentelemetry.appsignals.test.jdbc.AssertJNestedTest.test(AssertJNestedTest.java:32)
```

In this case I would expect the stacktrace to point to the assert inside the `isFive` method(line 39), but instead it is pointing to the outter assert.

Let me know if I'm missing something here or if there is already a way to show the actual failed assertion in the stack trace.

